<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
The non-papillate perithecia with warted surface, clavate asci with ellipsoidal to broadly ellipsoidal, uniseptate, striate ascospores, as well as our molecular data, suggest that this species belongs to 
<taxonomicName class="Sordariomycetes" genus="Rugonectria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Rugonectria" order="Hypocreales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Rugonectria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.68.03" author="Chaverri, P" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="57 - 68" refId="B6" refString="Chaverri, P, Salgado, C, Hirooka, Y, Rossman, AY, Samuels, GJ, 2011. Delimitation of Neonectria and Cylindrocarpon (Nectriaceae, Hypocreales, Ascomycota) and related genera with Cylindrocarpon-like anamorphs. . Studies in Mycology 68: 57 - 68" title="Delimitation of Neonectria and Cylindrocarpon (Nectriaceae, Hypocreales, Ascomycota) and related genera with Cylindrocarpon-like anamorphs." url="https://doi.org/10.3114/sim.2011.68.03" volume="68" year="2011">Chaverri et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). Amongst the known species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. microconidia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="microconidia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. microconidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is morphologically most similar to the type species, 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. rugulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="rugulosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. rugulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in having gregarious, warted, orange perithecia often with a dark red ostiole when dry (
<bibRefCitation author="Samuels, GJ" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="6 - 108" refId="B28" refString="Samuels, GJ, Doi, Y, Rogerson, CT, 1990. Hypocreales. . Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 59: 6 - 108" title="Hypocreales." volume="59" year="1990">Samuels et al. 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Samuels, GJ" journalOrPublisher="Sydowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="75 - 161" refId="B29" refString="Samuels, GJ, Brayford, D, 1994. Species of Nectria (sensu lato) with red perithecia and striate ascospores. . Sydowia 46: 75 - 161" title="Species of Nectria (sensu lato) with red perithecia and striate ascospores." volume="46" year="1994">Samuels and Brayford 1994</bibRefCitation>
). The newly described species differs in having asci that are 93-130 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(11
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)15–">-)15-</normalizedToken>
25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
and larger than those of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. rugulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="rugulosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. rugulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that are (53
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)64–83(–">-)64-83(-</normalizedToken>
95) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(7.5
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)11.3–15.5(–">-)11.3-15.5(-</normalizedToken>
17) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. In addition, the ascospores of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. microconidia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="microconidia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. microconidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also larger, 20-28 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-12 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
, while those of 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. rugulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="rugulosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. rugulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are (10
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)13.5–18(–">-)13.5-18(-</normalizedToken>
24) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(3.3
<normalizedToken originalValue="–)4.7–6.7(–">-)4.7-6.7(-</normalizedToken>
10) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
. Unlike 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. microconidia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="microconidia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. microconidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. rugulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="rugulosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. rugulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not produce macroconidia in culture (
<bibRefCitation author="Samuels, GJ" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="6 - 108" refId="B28" refString="Samuels, GJ, Doi, Y, Rogerson, CT, 1990. Hypocreales. . Memoirs of the New York Botanical Garden 59: 6 - 108" title="Hypocreales." volume="59" year="1990">Samuels et al. 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Samuels, GJ" journalOrPublisher="Sydowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="75 - 161" refId="B29" refString="Samuels, GJ, Brayford, D, 1994. Species of Nectria (sensu lato) with red perithecia and striate ascospores. . Sydowia 46: 75 - 161" title="Species of Nectria (sensu lato) with red perithecia and striate ascospores." volume="46" year="1994">Samuels and Brayford 1994</bibRefCitation>
). Sequence comparisons reveal that there are 21 bp, 21 bp, 12 bp and 22 bp divergences in the ACT, ITS, LSU and RPB1 regions, respectively, between 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. microconidia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="microconidia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. microconidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="R." lsidName="R. rugulosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="species" species="rugulosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. rugulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(YH1001). Both morphological and molecular data suggest that these species are distinct.
</paragraph>
